He is the man of the crowd.”Like many poets and philosophers through the ages, Poe stressed the significance of solitude.
In the twentieth century, the idea of solitude formed the center of Hannah Arendt’s thought.
In solitude, Arendt never longed for companionship or craved camaraderie because she was never truly alone.
?” The self, Arendt declared, “is the only one from whom you can never get away—except by ceasing to think.”The self, Arendt declared, ‘is the only one from whom you can never get away—except by ceasing to think.’Arendt’s warning is well worth remembering in our own time.
But, Arendt reminds us, if we lose our capacity for solitude, our ability to be alone with ourselves, then we lose our very ability to think.